AGI - The light on Pope Francis> turned off. Literally. Inside the Basilica of St. Paul Outside the Walls in Rome there is a long series of tondi> – lined on the band above the arches that divide the aisles – with portraits of all the pontiffs>, from San Pietro> to Bergoglio>. Only the Pope of the pontificate in progress > is illuminated by a light that makes it stand out on all others, who remain, therefore, in the shadow.
A few days ago the 'return' of shutdown' for Bergoglio> took place: immediately after his death > on 21 April >, even the light on his tondo was extinguished, as in the dark are the last Popes at his side, in chronological order, Benedict XVI> and John Paul II >.
&nbsp;
<div </div
&nbsp;
<h2> The wait for the successor
Under the image of Francis > the dates of his pontificate should still be affixed >: 2013-2025>, as well as for each Pope. When the successor > of Bergoglio> is nominated and before the new round becomes enlightened, the time of the Vatican mosaicists should be expected : according to the custodians of the Basilica of St. Paul > – so they tell the AGI – once elected the Pontiff, will be necessary at least two months > before the new effigy is represented and illuminated.
&nbsp;
<div </div
&nbsp;
<h2>The history of the gallery of Papi</h2>
The tradition of tondi>, made with the technique of mosaic > and gold background, began in the year 1847>, during the pontificate of Pius IX>. The idea of this gallery of tondi> has the roots in the ancient basilica, since they were also present in the latter although painted.
At present the rounds are 265> and the portraits are in good part fantasy >, except, of course, for the most recent ones >: the Papi > showing realistic facts > are those from the 16th century > onwards. The image of Pope Francis >, taken from a frame, had been realized at the beginning of his pontificate by the Studio del Mosaico Vaticano> of the Fabbrica di San Pietro > which, after the fire of 1823>, performed all rounds with the faces of the pontificates > for the Basilica in Via Ostiense.
&nbsp;
<div </div
&nbsp;
<h2> The legend and future rounds
For according to a legend? Christ will return when there will be no more sufficient space > for a new medallion under John Paul II >, being there only three free medallions >, another 25 rounds were made. At present in St. Paul's Basilica, this year a place of jubilee destination, there are 26 free medallions.
&nbsp;
